<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF109-449-621  </DOCNO><DOCID>09 449 621.andM;</DOCID><JOURNAL>Digital Review  Sept 24 1990 v7 n37 p22(1)* Full Text COPYRIGHT Cahners-Ziff Publishing Associates LP 1990.andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>Strategic misdirection. (DECville 1990 DEC conference) (editorial)</TITLE><AUTHOR>Fegreus, John.andM;</AUTHOR><DESCRIPT>Company:   Digital Equipment Corp. (conferences and meetings).andO;Ticker:    DEC.andO;Topic:     DECvilleTrade ShowsSeminars.andO;Feature:   illustrationcartoon.andM;</DESCRIPT><TEXT>Strategic misdirectionandM;For end users, DECville '90 in Cannes, France, proved the most telling ofDEC's worldwide gatherings.andP;  Free from all the hoopla surrounding DECworld inBoston, DECville resembled a very high-level DECUS symposium.andP;  Topinformation technology executives gathered to learn more about DEC'sstrategic direction and to share their own strategies for surviving in aturbulent computer market.andM;Even more enlightening than DEC's presentations, however, were the responsesand reactions of attendees.andM;For starters, it wasn't surprising that the sessions on Unix and open systemsplayed before standing-room--only crowds.andP;  As attendees streamed into theUnix symposium, they heard a background motif of new-age music accompanied byjungle sounds.andP;  Once the session started, the message was drummed home loudlyand clearly: Unix is a jungle of incompatible systems.andP;  The theme that Unixalone will not deliver applications portability and that programminginterface standards like the IEEE's Posix and X/Open's XPG3 (X PortabilityGuide) are essential struck a very sympathetic chord with the audience.andM;Logically, any operating system that adheres to these standards will provideeverything necessary for applications portability.andP;  The implication was notlost on DEC.andP;  At every opportunity,  DEC played on the theme of just howclosely VMS already complies with these key portability standards.andP;  Stressingits plans to completely incorporate all the portability standards into itsNetwork Application Support (NASA), DEC outlined its strategy to provide forportable and interoperable application software on both VMS and Ultrix.andM;This strident VMS counterpoint at the Unix meetings did not, however, playout exactly the way DEC had intended.andM;At a session for NAS, DEC posed a plaintive question: &quot;How many of you thinkDigital has a Unix strategy?&quot;andP;  Now you might guess that the answer was aresounding yes, given that DEC has long been one of the leading Unix systemssuppliers and that it has some of the hottest RISC workstations on the markettoday.andM;Guess again.andM;At a time when DEC's annual Unix market growth is 30 to 40 percent while itsVMS market growth is 5 to 6 percent, many end users are beginning to think ofNAS as an apologia for VMS.andP;  Worse yet, there are those who further mistakeNAS as a cover for no Unix strategy at all.andP;  For DEC, the challenge now is tostimulate that 5 to 6 percent VMS growth while not alienating the Unix side.andO;</TEXT></DOC>